Scope & Prioritize Accessibility Issues

02
On this page
  1. Scoping Accessibility Issues
  2. Prioritizing Accessibility Issues

Any validation you can do up front to try and get an estimate of how long it will take for issues to be fixed is something that product management will love. In these lessons, we’ll look at strategies for scoping & prioritization of accessibility Issues.

Scoping Accessibility Issues

As you’re trying to figure out a specific accessibility problem and you’re working within a system of individuals on a team, you might ask yourself:

How are we going to get people to actually adopt this?

How will we prioritize it so that it doesn't get put into the backlog and ignored?

We want to scope an issue so the rest of the team can act upon it. We want to prioritize it and communicate to the rest of the team that it is compelling work to pick up. Let’s discuss the following example CampSpots example. This one is more about prioritizing it and scoping it.

You can access the membership page for CampSpots by running the application locally or via the deployed site. To run the application locally you will need to clone and follow the README: https://github.com/testing-accessibility/workshop-design-people-skills

Several issues are happening here. The first issue is that content is still reachable on the main checkout page behind the modal when it is active. The second issue is that the focus must be sent into the modal when it becomes active, and back to the main page when the modal is closed.

We first need to scope these problems because right now, they’re too big for one issue and and have the potential to be closed if included all together. You will need to break these items down into tasks that your team can individually address. They might be part of a more significant project, like an Epic.

Breaking an epic into more practical stories helps understand a project and maintain momentum. There is no one-size-fits-all solution for creating stories from an epic. But the t-shirt size scale works well to estimate the level of effort. You can also start from small issues and work toward bigger issues to get some quick wins on your side.

To scope accessibility issues, specifically, here are some ideas that can be used individually or together to create impactful user stories. The goal is to break things down to an appropriate size to get picked up and handled in a timely fashion:

  • By the user’s input modality, such as keyboard, screen reader, or voice navigation
  • By component or component state
  • By WCAG success criteria

Prioritizing Accessibility Issues

Once you have scoped down an issue, your next step is to apply some prioritization criteria.

This prioritization task could happen when you open the issue, or it could be something you visit later as a team scoping exercise. Either way, it can help to reference WCAG when figuring out prioritization. Doing a quick search for “WCAG modal dialog focus”, for example, you’ll find Modal Dialog Example | WAI-ARIA Authoring Practices 1.2.

You can also search the web for a given pattern with the phrase “success criteria” in your query. If you are able to match a WCAG success criterion to the issue at hand, make note of the level (A, AA, or AAA). Level can be a good prioritization tool for accessibility issues.

For example, if you have a bunch of JIRA tickets at level A, those can be prioritized first. For any issues at level AA, they are still important to fix but they can come next in the queue. AAA issues are typically considered as time permits after A and AA issues have been addressed.

The main takeaway is that your prioritization process should have you doing the more user-impacting things first. This includes areas like lack of keyboard access, which falls under WCAG Level A and is a huge access barrier for sites and applications.
